  abstract = {With the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence (AI) in the hotel and tourism industry, AI agents are increasingly involved in online service recovery. This study examines how disclosing an AI agent's identity influences consumers' information distortion in online service recovery. Building on mind perception theory and psychological distance theory, we propose that AI agent identity disclosure reduces consumers' mind perception of service agents, which subsequently shapes cognitive trust and increases their tendency to distort information during service recovery interactions. Across two experimental studies using realistic hotel service recovery scenarios, we find consistent evidence for this serial mediation effect. Furthermore, the level of anthropomorphism moderates the relationship. This research advances the literature on AI transparency in hospitality and tourism by uncovering a previously overlooked psychological mechanism that drives consumer information distortion. The findings also provide practical guidance for hotel and tourism service providers to improve service recovery effectiveness.},
